  <introduction>
    <p>
      Introduction goes here.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        We can hold one variable constant to get a cross-section of a 3D surface.
        This is called a trace, and it's the same as looking at the intersection between a surface and a plane parallel to one of the coordinate planes.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Ellipsoid:
        <me>
          \frac{(x-x_{0})^{2}}{a^{2}}+\frac{(y-y_{0})^{2}}{b^{2}}+\frac{(z-z_{0})^{2}}{c^{2}}=1
        </me>
        Traces are all ellipses.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Hyperboloid of one sheet:
        <me>
          \frac{(x-x_{0})^{2}}{a^{2}}+\frac{(y-y_{0})^{2}}{b^{2}}-\frac{(z-z_{0})^{2}}{c^{2}}=1
        </me>
        Traces are ellipses or hyperbolas.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Hyperboloid of two sheets:
        <me>
          \frac{(x-x_{0})^{2}}{a^{2}}-\frac{(y-y_{0})^{2}}{b^{2}}-\frac{(z-z_{0})^{2}}{c^{2}}=1
        </me>
        Again traces are ellipses or hyperbolas, but one trace is empty, which gives two sheets.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Elliptic Paraboloid:
        <me>
          z=\frac{(x-x_{0})^{2}}{a^{2}}+\frac{(y-y_{0})^{2}}{b^{2}}
        </me>
        Traces are ellipses or parabolas.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Elliptic Paraboloid:
        <me>
          z=\frac{(x-x_{0})^{2}}{a^{2}}-\frac{(y-y_{0})^{2}}{b^{2}}
        </me>
        Traces are hyperbolas or parabolas.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>
